t6445.text: The forces of fossil fuel are banking on Australian apathy when it comes to climate change. But perhaps, just maybe, these horrendous climate fires could be the spark of cascading forms of change that can prove how Australians can lead the world to a better place.

t6446.text: Climate people power requires more than a protest. We need a long term movement that unites across all the divisions exploited in the last election - between cities and regions, across jobs and the environment, across classes and races. We need a plan for the economy.

t6447.text: The political class, and Morrison in particular, is banking on the outrage passing when the smoke fades. There are signs that anger will linger. Protests are planned for 4 Feb. But more than this will be needed. Can the angry create a pressure that can’t be ignored?

t6448.text: The lack of political leadership on the climate fires has unintentionally created the space for a beautiful messy outrage from the everyday of us. Christmas dinners, shopping queues, public transport chats have become a new place to share fire anger and plan what to do about it.

t6449.text: In civil society, it is embryonic social movements like the student climate strikers ( @StrikeClimate)and Extinction @XRebellionAus that are taking action on the fires. Many of the established Enviro NGOs are on a break or not cutting through.

t6450.text: Australia doesn’t just a lack of political party accountability (too much ALP/greens tit for tat, and too little planning for how to win on climate action). The problems are in civil society too.

t6451.text: Accountability is the fundamental condition of democratic political life. And it’s absence during the climate bushfires is what makes this moment so new. No media accountability sure, but also very little political accountability.https://twitter.com/rgcooke/status/1212527989314871296 …
